UML:TaggedValue.value: Add, show and modify a receipt: UC to allow the elderly to add a receipt in the system following a multimedia wizard. The user can add ingredients, cooking techniques and even photographs of the process, to be shown later in time for example when cooking or whenever the user wants. The user can also ask for the visualization of a receipt, the ingredients of the receipt (with probability of availability at home) a concrete technique (with the associated risks).

Describes the process of doing the shopping using an eCommerce platform available through an internet connection. The items are sent at user’s home without his intervention. The shopping list should be remotely updated according to the acquired items.

Defines the process by which the system is able to build e.g. the weekly shopping list to the user based on several input information: the personalized menu created by the system and the availability of basic products which amount can be measured somehow.
Once initial profile is built, MD completes user’s profile with medical information after checking explicit user’s profile.

System generates the menu for the whole week according to health status, nutritional profile, user preferences. Also take into account the food existences to select the dishes to be incorporated. These preferences are related to meal times, likes, dislikes,…

Avatar asks AP every day how he feels and if he needs any suggestions for spending the day. If AP wants the system will inform him for instance about interesting community events or TV programmes or contacts to neighbours

The menu proposed by the system can be modified by the user according to his/her preferences or particular situation. The user can exchange meals between days or select alternative meals or mark a specific meal time to be performed outside (in a restaurant, in relative/friend home…)

Personal Calendar is an environment for scheduling/managing the daily tasks of the elderly (managing nutrition, medication, to-do lists, etc.) User, together with carer, constructing and updating his/her personal calendar by adding daily/weekly/monthly events or casual one (i.e. medicine uptake, family members’ birthdays, appointments with friends or nurses). The calendar notifies all participants of the event about the appointment and enables them to reply.The calendar informs user about potential overlap in calendar events.The personal calendar remindes to the user about upcoming events in his calendar (i.e. alarm).The personal calendar allows other users (i.e. caregivers, doctors, nurses, friends) to see the personal calendar (or part of it), to provide inputs (i.e. new plan of treatment, request for new appointment etc) and to receive response from the Subject of Care.
User requests to view this week planned menu at different levels of details (week, day, meal time, nutritional properties). This UC could be triggered at home or on the move

analysis of information related to the situations of the user executed by a data mining module that analyzes the data according to some predefined rules (user behavior profile) and produces some conclusions. The example behaviors to monitor are: 1) food intake and nutritional habits, 2) activities in the bathroom (how many times, if uses the WC in a normal way…), 3) Sleeping patterns, 4) General safety issues (too many times the system detected that the oven was on for 3 hours, or door not unlocked when the user went outside…), 5) Social relationships (does the user leave home?, does he receive friends?). Conclusions from the data analysis are stored and can produce a sequence of actions: the most important, informs a health assistant, inform the user about his habits; inform a relative…). The system can also detect erratic behavior (checks the user agenda for getting any appointment that justify the user behavior) and initiate emergency procedure.

This UC deals with the characterisation of human activities (daily activities, exercise) through the calculation of parameters. The parameters previously gathered are recorded and analysed with algorithms that allow to determine other parameters such as daily energy expenditure, physical activity level, etc. Finally a link between activity an physiological parameters completes the characterization of the activity and its impact on the elderly.

This use case is in charge of creating the medication program (task of the health professional) and of keeping track of the user's medication schedule, medication history and the conformance of the user to this schedule. It is also responsible to remind the user to take his/her medication and to inform him/her on possible changes in medication (decided by the doctor). The system gives feedback to the user. The user can check the medication info remotely

The user's profile information(activity,health,nutrition) is gathered implicitly without asking directly to the person but getting the responses, acts and interactions with other parts of the system . The system sends back the gathered information to the professional/medical center.

There it is described the list of behaviors to monitor, and which basic information is needed to be stored by the system for the further analysis and in this profile are also described the list of actions derived from a concrete alert. UML:UseCase.name: Travelling partner helping out of home

UML:TaggedValue.value: The main aim of the UC is to provide the user with support when travelling out of his natural and usual environment while focusing on the position of the user in the current environment. The system should identify the new environment and propose to the user new geographically based social communities in line with his interests and preferences, get instant contactless information (online, Bluetooth or NFC), help find the best transportation including requesting a DRT service and ticket purchasing (NFC, online..). A user, after using a service, chooses to send feeback to the developer: Step1: User activates feedback Step 2: User can select to send usage data or a personal message (or both) Step 3: User writes a message and clicks send Step 4: Developer gets the message (and usage data) in his inbox related to the service.

The developer specifies some search criteria (e.g. target platform spec) and browses (via web intreface or IDE plugin) the depotServer for suitable libraries, services and configurations that he could use for developing his own services, components etc.

Different schemes of billing (assigning of a value for using or posesing the service) and payment (re-imbursment of the costs) should be specified. Possible scenarios: 1. User-uStore-SP - Here the SP acts as middleman that could have its own charging policy. For example, the user has a contract with the uStore from where he gets a package of services and pays monthly fee to uStore. On other side uStore deals independently with the SP refunding the consumed service. The SP does not know who has consumed the service 2. uStore just enables direct communication between user and SP. In this case, the user has own account by the SP and refunds directly to the SP the consumed service. Charging schemes: per use, per time, per volume, per installation, obtaining a token/ticket unlocking the service. pre-paid, abo, post-paid?

When the AP starts an interaction with an AAL Service, it delegates the proper rendering of the GUI to the platform, so that GUI should be "Friendly", which stands for whether the GUI is understandable enough by the user. An AAL Service needs to use another AAL service but it is not available. It asks the platform to warn it once such a service is available. The system should search for alternative providers of the same service - execute a remote service or download ad hoc the "replacement" service.

Most of the existing devices in market should be supported by universAAL. An AAL Service needs that a certain device makes a certain action, and this device is not specifically controlled by the service itself but is a device that is part of the system. The service interacts with that device regardless of the technology thanks to the platform.
